SIMPLE: treaty
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Treaty
<hw>Trea"ty</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Treaties</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>tretee</ets>, F.
<ets>trait⟦eacute⟧</ets>, LL. <ets>tractatus</ets>; cf. L.
<ets>tractatus</ets> a handling, treatment, consultation, tractate. See
<er>Treat</er>, and cf. <er>Tractate</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
act of treating for the adjustment of differences, as for forming an
agreement; negotiation.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧By sly and wise
<xex>treaty</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He cast by <qex>treaty</qex> and by trains⟦br⟧
Her to persuade.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An agreement so made; specifically, an agreement,
league, or contract between two or more nations or sovereigns, formally
signed by commissioners properly authorized, and solemnly ratified by
the several sovereigns, or the supreme power of each state; an agreement
between two or more independent states; <as>as, a <ex>treaty</ex> of
peace; a <ex>treaty</ex> of alliance.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A proposal tending to an agreement.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A treatise; a tract.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Treble</ent>⟦br⟧
